  <li><p><m>\log_b \left(\dfrac{x}{y} \right) = </m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\log_b (x^m) = </m></p></li>
</ol></p></task>

        <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
        <p>To help your students understand the log properties, look at some numerical examples, as in part (a), alongside the corresponding property of exponents. Highlight the fact that the logarithms are the exponents.</p></commentary>

<task><p>Verify that the properties are true for these examples by calculating the logs:</p>
<p>Property (1):</p>
    <p><md><mrow>~~~~\log_2 32 = \log_2 (4 \cdot 8) \amp = \log_2 4 + \log_2 8 ~~~~~~~~~~ \text{because} ~2^5 = 2^2 \cdot 2^3)</mrow>
      <mrow><fillin/> \amp = <fillin/> + <fillin/></mrow></md></p>
<p>Property (2):</p>
    <p><md><mrow>~~~~\log_2 8 = \log_2 \left(\dfrac{16}{2} \right)\amp  = \log_2 16 - \log_2 2 ~~~~~~~~~~ \text{because} ~2^3 = \dfrac{2^4}{2^1}</mrow>
    <mrow><fillin/> \amp = <fillin/> - <fillin/></mrow></md></p>
<p>Property (3):</p>
    <p><md><mrow>~~~~\log_2 64 = \log_2 (4^3) \amp = 3\log_2 4 ~~~~~~~~~~  \text{because} ~(2^2)^3 = 2^6</mrow>
    <mrow><fillin/> \amp = <fillin/> \times <fillin/></mrow></md></p></task>

<task><p>Given that <m>\log_b 2 = 0.6931,~ \log_b 3 = 1.0986,~</m> and <m>\log_b 5 = 1.6094~</m>,  use the properties to simplify each expression.</p>
<p><ol>
  <li><p><m>\log_b 3x</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\log_b \dfrac{5}{x}</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\log_b 8</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\log_b \sqrt{5x}</m></p></li>
</ol></p></task>

<task><p>Caution! Be careful when using the properties of logarithms. Which expressions in each group are equivalent (if any)?</p>
<p><ol>

          <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
          <p>Point out the various incorrect applications of the log properties that studetns are prone to make.</p></commentary>

  <li><p><m>\log \dfrac{x}{25}~~~~~~~~\dfrac{\log x}{\log 25}~~~~~~~~\log x - \log 25~~~~~~~~\log (x-25)</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\log (25x)~~~~~~~~\log 25 + \log x~~~~~~~~\log (x+25)~~~~~~~~\log x \log 25</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>\log (x^2)~~~~~~~~(\log x)^2~~~~~~~~2 \log x~~~~~~~~\log 2x</m></p></li>
</ol></p></task>
</activity>

<activity><title>Solving Exponential Equations</title>

        <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
        <p>We use a two-step strategy for solving the exponential equations we study. We (1) isolate the exponential expression, then (2) take the log of both sides.</p></commentary>
 
 <introduction><p> Now we can solve exponential equations to any base, by using the third log property.</p></introduction>

<task><p>Follow the steps to solve the equation  <m>~~3^x = 25</m></p>   

  <p>Take the log base 10 of both sides.</p>

  <p>Apply the third log property.</p>

  <p>Divide both sides by  <m>\log 3</m>.</p>

  <p>Use a calculator to obtain an approximation to 4 decimal places.</p></task>

          <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
          <p>When solving exponential equations, students may try to evaluate <m>\dfrac{\log a}{\log b}</m> as <m>\log \left(\dfrac{a}{b} \right)</m>, either by misapplying the log property, or by failing to use parentheses on the calculator.</p></commentary>

<task><p>Solve <m>~12 \cdot 5^{1.5x} = 85</m></p></task>

<task><p>Starting in 1998, the demand for electricity in Ireland grew at a rate of 5.8% per year. In 1998, 20,500 gigawatts were used. Write a formula for electricity demand in Ireland as a function of time.</p>

<p>When did demand reach 30,000 gigawatts?</p></task>
</activity>

